The electronâ€“electron local field correction (LFC) modifies the electron response to account for short-range correlations and exchange effects beyond the mean-field approximation.

Local field corrections :math:`G` describe exchange correlation effects. The
full linear susceptibility can be written as

.. math::

    \chi_\text{ee} =
    \frac{\chi_\text{ee}^\text{0}}{1 - V_{\text{ee}}
    (1 - G) \chi_\text{ee}^\text{0}}\quad


where :math:`V_{\text{ee}}` is the Coulomb potential between two electrons and :math:`\chi_\text{ee}^\text{0}` is Lindhard's function. While this is formally correct, :math:`G` is practically often unknown and has to be approximated.

Currently, only static and effective static approximations of the local field corrections are treated in `jaxrts`.
